{{use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{use British English|date=January 2015}} '''Alfred Nicholson Leeds''' (9 March 1847{{snd}}25 August 1917) was an English [[amateur]] [[Paleontology|palaeontologist]].
He was born at Eyebury, [[Peterborough]], the youngest of the eight children of Edward Thurlow Leeds (1802{{ndash}}51) and Eliza Mary Leeds (née Nicholson). He was educated at [[Warwick School]]. He had wanted to become a doctor, but circumstances meant that from 1868 he had to take on the management of Eyebury Farm (in [[The Fens]], and historically attached to [[Peterborough Cathedral|Peterborough Abbey]]) as a [[Gentleman's farm|gentleman farmer]].
His elder brother Charles, a student at [[Oxford University]], had been encouraged by Professor [[John Phillips (geologist)|John Phillips]] to persevere in collecting [[fossil]]s from near his home. Alfred joined him in these searches, and between them they developed better methods of disinterring, and of scientifically recording, fossils in soft [[clay]] than had been used before. (They rewarded the workmen at the clay pits (which served a brickworks in [[Fletton]], Peterborough) for not doing so themselves, but instead sending notice to Eyebury.)
In 1887, Charles emigrated to New Zealand; but Alfred continued to search for fossils, assisted by his wife and by their second son, [[Edward Thurlow Leeds]] (1877{{ndash}}1955, [[Curator|Keeper]] of the [[Ashmolean Museum]] 1928{{ndash}}45).
He amassed one of the largest collections of fossil vertebrates in the world. In 1889, his portrait was painted by the 17-year-old [[William Nicholson (artist)|William Nicholson]]. From 1890 onwards, he began to present his most important specimens of [[Jurassic]] fossils from the [[Oxford Clay]] near Peterborough to the [[British Museum]]. He was a Fellow of the [[Geological Society of London|Geological Society]]; in 1893, he was awarded part of its [[Charles Lyell|Lyell]] Fund.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayFulltext?type=1&fid=5115308&jid=GEO&volumeId=4&issueId=10&aid=5115304 |title=Obituary - Alfred Nicholson Leeds |author=A. S. W. |authorlink=Arthur Smith Woodward |journal=Geological Magazine |year=1917 |volume=4 |issue=10 |page=478 |accessdate=7 January 2015 |doi=10.1017/s0016756800136507}}</ref>
Other museums in the UK and elsewhere hold items from his collection; including the [[National Museum of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://plesiosauria.com/pdf/araujo_etal_2008.pdf |last1=Araújo |first1=Ricardo |last2=Smith |first2=Adam S. |last3=Liston |first3=Jeff |title=The Alfred Leeds Fossil Vertebrate Collection of the National Museum of Ireland – Natural History |journal=Irish Journal of Earth Sciences |volume=26 |year=2008 |pages=17{{ndash}}32 |accessdate=7 January 2015 |doi=10.3318/ijes.2008.26.17}}</ref>
An extinct [[genus]] of fish, ''[[Leedsichthys]]'', and several extinct [[species]] have been named in his honour.
== Discoveries and honours == * Early 1880s{{snd}}he acquired the skeleton of a [[Stegosauria|stegosaur]] [[dinosaur]] found in a brick pit near [[Eye, Cambridgeshire]]. In 1887, it was [[Species description|described]] by [[John Whitaker Hulke]] as a new [[species]], ''[[Omosaurus]] durobrivensis''. It is now considered to be within the [[genus]] ''[[Lexovisaurus]]''. * 1880s{{snd}}he collected fossils of a large [[Mesozoic]] [[Osteichthyes|bony fish]], which proved to be from the novel genus ''Leedsichthys'', described and named in his honour by [[Arthur Smith Woodward]] in 1889. * 1887{{snd}}Hulke described a species of sauropod, ''[[Ornithopsis]] leedsi'', naming it in his honour. It has been since been renamed ''[[Cetiosauriscus]] leedsi''. * 1889{{snd}}the [[type species]] of a genus of [[iguanodont]]ian dinosaur was named ''[[Camptosaurus]] leedsi'' in his honour by [[Richard Lydekker]]. It has since been renamed ''[[Callovosaurus]] leedsi'', * 1893{{snd}}Lydekker named the type species of a genus of [[ankylosauria]]n [[ornithischia]]n dinosaur ''[[Sarcolestes]] leedsi'' in his honour. * 1901{{snd}}[[Harry Seeley]] described a species of stegosaur ''[[Omosaurus]] leedsi'', naming it in his honour. The genus has since been renamed ''[[Dacentrurus]]''. * 1907-09{{snd}}he collected a fossil, which in 2013 proved to be the sole species of a [[geosaurine]] [[metriorhynchid]] [[crocodyliform]] known within the genus ''[[Tyrannoneustes]]''.
== See also == * {{cite book |last=Andrews |first=C. W. |authorlink=Charles William Andrews |year=1910 |title=A Descriptive Catalogue of the Marine Reptiles of the Oxford Clay, Based on the Leeds Collection in the British Museum (Natural History), Part I |location=London |publisher=British Museum }} * {{cite book |last=Andrews |first=C. W. |year=1913 |title=A Descriptive Catalogue of the Marine Reptiles of the Oxford Clay, Part II |location=London |publisher=British Museum }} * {{cite book |last=Leeds |first=E. T. |authorlink=Edward Thurlow Leeds |year=1956 |title=The Leeds Collection of Fossil Reptiles from the Oxford Clay of Peterborough |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell|Blackwell Ltd]] |location=Oxford }}
