{{no footnotes|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox glacier | child = | name = Amundsen Glacier | other_name = | photo = | photo_width = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | map = Antarctica | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of Amundsen Glacier in [[Antarctica]] | mark = Blue_pog.svg | type = | location = [[Ross Dependency]] | coordinates = {{coord|78|17|S|163|4|E|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline}} | coords_ref = | area = | length = {{convert|128|km|mi|abbr=on}} | width = {{convert|10|km|mi|abbr=on}} | thickness = | elevation_max = | elevation_min = | terminus = [[Ross Ice Shelf]] | status = | embedded = }}
'''Amundsen Glacier''' ({{coord|85|35|S|159|00|W|type:glacier_region:AQ|display=inline,title}}) is a major [[Antarctica|Antarctic]] [[glacier]], about 6 to 10&nbsp;km (4 to 6&nbsp;mi) wide and 128&nbsp;km (80&nbsp;mi) long, originating on the [[polar plateau]] where it drains the area to the south and west of Nilsen Plateau, and descending through the [[Queen Maud Mountains]] to enter the [[Ross Ice Shelf]] just west of the MacDonald [[Nunatak]]s. The tributary [[Blackwall Glacier]] flows northwest along the northeast side of [[Hansen Spur]] to join Amundsen Glacier.
It was discovered by [[Richard E. Byrd|Rear Admiral Byrd]] on the [[South Pole]] flight in November 1929. The name was proposed for [[Roald Amundsen]] by Laurence Gould, leader of the Byrd AE geological party which sledged past the mouth of the glacier in December 1929.
==See also== * [[List of glaciers in the Antarctic]] * [[Glaciology]]
