assment]]{{·}}[[Homesickness]]{{·}}[[Humiliation]]{{·}}[[Emotional insecurity|Insecurity]]{{·}}[[Insult]]{{·}}[[Isolation (psychology)|Isolation]]{{·}}[[Loneliness]]{{·}}[[Social rejection|Rejection]]'' |- |''[[Sympathy]]||''[[Pity]]''{{·}}''[[Mono no aware]]''{{·}}''[[Sympathy]]'' |- |rowspan="2"|[[Fear]]||''[[Horror and terror|Horror]]||''[[Wiktionary:alarm|Alarm]]{{·}}[[Acute stress reaction|Shock]]{{·}}Fear{{·}}[[Wiktionary:fright|Fright]]{{·}}Horror{{·}}[[Wiktionary:terror|Terror]]{{·}}[[Panic]]{{·}}[[Hysteria]]{{·}}[[Wiktionary:mortification|Mortification]]'' |- |''[[Anxiety|Nervousness]]||''[[Wiktionary:anxiety|Anxiety]]{{·}}[[Suspense]]{{·}}[[Wiktionary:uneasiness|Uneasiness]]{{·}}[[Wiktionary:apprehension|Apprehension (fear)]]{{·}}[[Worry]]{{·}}[[Wiktionary:distress|Distress]]{{·}}[[Wiktionary:dread|Dread]]'' |}''
===Plutchik's wheel of emotions=== [[Image:Plutchik-wheel.svg|Plutchik's Wheel of Emotions. Similar emotions in the wheel are adjacent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JaQauznPoiEC&pg=PA34&dq=robert+plutchik's+the+nature+of+emotions&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjS14-9iKnWAhVHDcAKHTpNCEoQuwUIMzAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Emotions|first=Robert|last=Plutchik|date=16 September 1991|publisher=University Press of America|accessdate=16 September 2017|via=Google Books|page=110}}</ref>|350px|thumb|right]] In 1980, [[Robert Plutchik]] constructed diagram of emotions visualising eight basic emotions: joy, trust, fear, surprise, sadness, disgust, anger and anticipation. The wheel was inspired by ''Plutchik's Ten Postulates''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personalityresearch.org/basicemotions/plutchik.html|title=Basic Emotions—Plutchik|website=Personalityresearch.org|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://americanscientist.org/articles/01articles/Plutchik.html |title=The Nature of Emotions |publisher=American Scientist |last=Plutchik |first=R |authorlink=Robert Plutchik |accessdate=14 April 2011 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010716082847/http://americanscientist.org/articles/01articles/Plutchik.html |archivedate=July 16, 2001 }} </ref> Plutchik also theorized twenty-four "Primary", "Secondary", and "Tertiary" dyads (feelings composed of two emotions).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adliterate.com/archives/Plutchik.emotion.theorie.POSTER.pdf |format=PDF |title=Robert Plutchik's Psychoevolutionary Theory of Basic Emotions |website=Adliterate.com |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref><ref name="Turner2000">{{cite book|author=Jonathan Turner|title=On the Origins of Human Emotions: A Sociological Inquiry Into the Evolution of Human Affect|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aEeSmDRsXkcC&pg=PA76|date=1 June 2000|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-6436-0|page=76}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=A Fuzzy Inference System for Synergy Estimation of Simultaneous Emotion Dynamics in Agents|journal=International Journal of Scientific & Engineering Research|volume=2|issue=6|date=June 2011|url=http://www.ijser.org/paper/A_Fuzzy_Inference_System_for_Synergy_Estimation_of_Simultaneous_Emotion_Dynamics_in_Agents.html|author1=Atifa Athar|author2=M. Saleem Khan|author3=Khalil Ahmed|author4=Aiesha Ahmed|author5=Nida Anwar}} </ref> The wheel emotions can be paired in four groups: : Primary dyad = one petal apart = '''Love''' = ''Joy'' + ''Trust'' : Secondary dyad = two petals apart = '''Envy''' = ''Sadness'' + ''Anger'' : Tertiary dyad = three petals apart = '''Shame''' = ''Fear'' + ''Disgust'' : Opposite emotions = four petals apart = ''Anticipation'' ≠ ''Surprise'' Emotions can be mild or intense;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emotionalcompetency.com/papers/plutchiknatureofemotions%202001.pdf|format=PDF|title=The Nature of Emotions|website=Emotionalcompetency.com|accessdate=2017-09-16}}</ref> for example, distraction is a mild form of surprise, and rage is an intense form of anger. The kinds of relation between each pair of emotions are:
{|class="wikitable" |+ Emotions and opposites |- ! Mild emotion ! Mild opposite ! Basic emotion ! Basic opposite ! Intense emotion ! Intense opposite |- | [[Wiktionary:serenity|Serenity]] || ''[[Melancholia|Pensiveness]]'' || [[Joy]] || ''[[Sadness]]'' || [[Ecstasy (emotion)|Ecstasy]] || ''[[Grief]]'' |- | [[Acceptance]] || ''[[Boredom]]'' || [[Trust (emotion)|Trust]] || ''[[Disgust]]'' || [[Admiration]] || ''[[Wiktionary:loathing|Loathing]]'' |- | [[Wiktionary:apprehension|Apprehension]] || ''[[Annoyance]]'' || [[Fear]] || ''[[Anger]]'' || [[wikt:terror|Terror]] || ''[[Rage (emotion)|Rage]]'' |- | [[Distraction]] || ''[[Interest (emotion)|Interest]] || [[Surprise (emotion)|Surprise]] || ''[[Anticipation (emotion)|Anticipation]]'' || [[Wiktionary:amazement|Amazement]] || ''[[Vigilance (psychology)|Vigilance]]'' |}''
{|class="wikitable" |+ Dyads (Combinations) |- ! Human feelings ! Emotions ! Opposite feelings ! Emotions |- | [[Optimism]] || Anticipation + Joy || ''[[Disappointment|Disapproval]]'' || Surprise + Sadness |- | [[Hope]] || Anticipation + Trust || ''[[Wiktionary:unbelief|Unbelief]]'' || Surprise + Disgust |- | [[Anxiety]] || Anticipation + Fear || ''[[Outrage (emotion)|Outrage]]'' || Surprise + Anger |- | [[Love]] || Joy + Trust || ''[[Remorse]]'' || Sadness + Disgust |- | [[Guilt (emotion)|Guilt]] || Joy + Fear || ''[[Envy]]'' || Sadness + Anger |- | [[Pleasure|Delight]] || Joy + Surprise || ''[[Pessimism]]'' || Sadness + Anticipation |- | [[Deference|Submission]] || Trust + Fear || ''[[Contempt]]'' || Disgust + Anger |- | [[Curiosity]] || Trust + Surprise || ''[[Cynicism (contemporary)|Cynicism]]'' || Disgust + Anticipation |- | [[Sentimentality]] || Trust + Sadness || ''[[wikt:morbidness|Morbidness]]'' || Disgust + Joy |- | [[Awe]] || Fear + Surprise || ''[[Aggressiveness]]'' || Anger + Anticipation |- | [[Despair]] || Fear + Sadness || ''[[Pride]]'' || Anger + Joy |- | [[Shame]] || Fear + Disgust || ''[[Expressions of dominance|Dominance]]'' || Anger + Trust |}
===Plutchik's wheel in Venn format=== Jessica Hagy wrote on her blog that Plutchik's wheel of emotions gave a demonstration on emotions, but needed more levels of intensity in the emotion combinations. She observed that the wheel was a [[Venn diagram]] format, and expanded the primary dyads.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thisisindexed.com/2012/07/plutchiks-wheel-of-emotions |title=Plutchik's Wheel of Emotions – Indexed |website=Thisisindexed.com |date=2012-07-06 |accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref> {|class="wikitable" |+ Emotional overlap |- ! Human feelings ! Emotions ! Opposite feelings ! Emotions |- | [[Wiktionary:bemusement|Bemusement]] || Interest + Serenity || ''[[Wiktionary:dismay|Dismay]]'' || Distraction + Pensiveness |- | [[Wiktionary:zeal|Zeal]] || Vigilance + Ecstasy || ''[[Wiktionary:horror|Horror]]'' || Amazement + Grief |- | [[Wiktionary:acknowledgment|Acknowledgement]] || Serenity + Acceptance || ''[[Listlessness]]'' || Pensiveness + Boredom |- | [[Wiktionary:devotion|Devotion]] || Ecstasy + Admiration || ''[[Shame]]'' || Grief + Loathing |- | [[Wiktionary:acquiescence|Acquiescence]] || Acceptance + Apprehension || ''[[Impatience]]'' || Boredom + Annoyance |- | [[Wiktionary:subservience|Subservience]] || Admiration + Terror || ''[[Hatred]]'' || Loathing + Rage |- | [[Wiktionary:wariness|Wariness]] || Apprehension + Distraction || ''[[Wiktionary:disfavor|Disfavor]]'' || Annoyance + Interest |- | [[Wiktionary:petrification|Petrification]] || Terror + Amazement || ''[[Wiktionary:domination|Domination]]'' || Rage + Vigilance |}
===The Hourglass of Emotions=== [[File:Hourglass-advancedemotions.png|thumb|400px|Advanced emotions formed from two sentic dimensions.]] The 2012 book '''The Hourglass of Emotions''' was based on Robert Plutchik's model, but categorised the emotions into four sentic dimensions. It contrasted anger, anticipation, joy, and trust as positive emotions, and fear, surprise, sadness and disgust as negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sentic.net/hourglass-of-emotions.pdf |title=LNCS 7403 – The Hourglass of Emotions |format=PDF |website=Sentic.net |date= |accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref> {|class="wikitable" |+ Emotional flow |- ! Dimension ! +3 ! +2 ! +1 ! -1 ! -2 ! -3 |- ![[wikt:sensitivity|Sensitivity]] | [[Rage (emotion)|Rage]] || [[Anger]] || [[Annoyance]] || [[Wiktionary:apprehension|Apprehension]] || [[Fear]] || [[Wiktionary:terror|Terror]] |- ![[Attention]] | [[Vigilance (psychology)|Vigilance]] || [[Anticipation (emotion)|Anticipation]] || [[Interest (emotion)|Interest]] || [[Distraction]] || [[Surprise (emotion)|Surprise]] || [[Wiktionary:amazement|Amazement]] |- ![[Pleasantness]] | [[Ecstasy (emotion)|Ecstasy]] || [[Joy]] || [[wikt:serenity|Serenity]] || [[Melancholia|Pensiveness]] || [[Sadness]] || [[Grief]] |- ![[Aptitude]]'' | [[Admiration]] || [[Trust (emotion)|Trust]] || [[Acceptance]] || [[Boredom]] || [[Disgust]] || [[Wiktionary:loathing|Loathing]] |},''
{|class="wikitable" |+ Advanced emotions |- ! Dimensions ! High Sensitivity ! Low Sensitivity ! High Pleasantness ! Low Pleasantness |- !High Attention | [[Aggressiveness]] || [[Anxiety]] || [[Optimism]] || [[Frustration]] |- !Low Attention | [[Social rejection|Rejection]] || [[Awe]] || [[Frivolity]] || [[Disappointment|Disapproval]] |- !High Aptitude | [[wikt:rivalry|Rivalry]] || [[Deference|Submission]] || [[Love]] || [[Envy]] |- !Low Aptitude | [[Contempt]] || [[Coercion]] || [[wikt:gloat|Gloat]] || [[Remorse]] |}
