{{Infobox book | name = The Birth and Death of the Sun | image = The Birth and Death of the Sun -- bookcover 1.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[George Gamow]] | illustrator = [[George Gamow]] | published = June 1940 | publisher = [[Viking Press]] | subject = Science, astronomy | genre = | isbn = | dewey = 523 pp | media_type = Print | congress = QB44 .G26 | oclc = 804206 | pages = 280 | website = {{URL|https://archive.org/details/birthanddeathoft032626mbp}} }}
'''''The Birth and Death of the Sun''''' is a popular science book by theoretical physicist and cosmologist [[George Gamow]], first published in 1940, exploring [[Chemistry|atomic chemistry]], [[stellar evolution]], and [[cosmology]].<ref name="Gamow-1940">{{cite book|author1=Gamow, George|authorlink1=George Gamow|title=The Birth and Death of the Sun|date=June 1940|publisher=[[Viking Press]]|location=New York|pages=ix–xi|url=https://archive.org/details/birthanddeathoft032626mbp|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref> The book is illustrated by Gamow. It was revised in 1952.
==Reception== Critical reception has been positive.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviewed Works: Public Opinion by Walter Lippmann; Patterns of Culture by Ruth Benedict; The Birth and Death of the Sun by George Gamow; You and Music by Christian Darnton|journal=Journal of Educational Sociology|date=January 1947|volume=20|issue=5|pages=314–315|doi=10.2307/2263833|jstor=2263833}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=F. R. M.|title=Evolution of the Physical Universe|journal=The Scientific Monthly|date=October 1940|volume=51|issue=4|page=373|jstor=17358|bibcode=1940SciMo..51..373G}}</ref> In February 1941, Gerard F. W. Mulders gave a favorable review for ''The Birth and Death of the Sun'', writing that "[i]t gives authentic information in nontechnical language from which mathematical formulae have been completely eliminated. The entertaining presentation of the most modern developments in physics and astrophysics, the sparkling humor, and the original drawings and graphs will be enjoyed by scientist and amateur alike."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mulders|first1=Gerard F. W.|title=Reviewed Work: The Birth and Death of the Sun; Stellar Evolution and Subatomic Energy by George Gamow|journal=Publications of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific|date=February 1941|volume=53|issue=311|pages=56–58|jstor=40670486|doi=10.1086/125268|bibcode=1941PASP...53...54.}}</ref>
In April 2015, physicist and Nobel laureate [[Steven Weinberg]] included ''The Birth and Death of the Sun'' in a personal list of "the 13 best science books for the general reader".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weinberg|first1=Steven|authorlink1=Steven Weinberg|title=Steven Weinberg: the 13 best science books for the general reader|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/03/steven-weinberg-13-best-science-books-general-reader|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 June 2015|date=3 April 2015}}</ref>
